 For Jewish women, salon leadership offered not only an escape from a restricted home life but also social and personal power, power that was frequently consolidated in their upwardly mobile marriages to noblemen. However advantageous and stimulating these salons were for their participants, they were the product of a transitory convergence of social and cultural structures. Hertz concludes by exploring how both underground antisemitic gossip and the new patriotism unleashed by the upheavals in Prussia after 1806 destroyed Jewish salon life in Berlin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311063899840uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300242713?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300242713423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300242713/original  a978-3-11-063899-8  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles